          "body": "To feel the weight of Isaiah 23 the reader must grasp what Tyre was. She was not merely a prosperous city; she was the connective tissue of ancient Mediterranean commerce. Her ships ran Egyptian grain to Aegean ports, Levantine cedar to temple-builders from Jerusalem to Nineveh, purple dye to the royal courts of the entire known world. Ezekiel 27-28 gives the fullest picture — Tyre's trading partners ranged from Tarshish in the west to Persia and Arabia in the east, from the Black Sea coasts to the Nile delta. Her merchants were, as Isaiah says, 'princes' (23:8). She did not merely participate in the global economy; she largely created it. To announce Tyre's destruction was to announce the collapse of the economic order that held the ancient world together. The anguish of Egypt (23:5) and the wailing of Tarshish's ships (23:1, 14) are not mourning a city — they are mourning a system."
