          "body": "Verse 18 is the chapter's most theologically stunning moment and one of the Old Testament's most surprising reversals. The profit of the harlot-city — earned by commercial promiscuity, by playing fast with all the kingdoms of the earth — is declared 'set apart (qodesh) to the LORD.' The Hebrew qodesh is the word for holiness, for that which is separated from common use to sacred use. Deuteronomy 23:18 explicitly prohibited bringing a prostitute's wages into the house of the LORD. Isaiah's reversal is deliberate: the very category of offering that was prohibited becomes the eschatological offering Tyre makes. This is not the same as endorsing Tyre's practices; it is the declaration that God's sovereign purposes are capable of transfiguring even corrupted wealth into sacred provision — 'sufficient food and choice attire for those who dwell in the presence of the LORD.' John Oswalt (NICOT on Isaiah) reads this as a foreshadowing of the eschatological gathering of Gentile wealth into the service of God's people (cf. Isaiah 60:5-7; 61:6). The chapter that opened with wailing over destruction closes with consecrated abundance — not because Tyre repented, but because the LORD of hosts, who planned the destruction, also plans the redemption."
